4. Wind and Solar as Variable Sources

Wind and solar are variable energy sources.

When their output fluctuates:

The battery compensates by discharging.

It ensures continuous power supply.

5. Grid vs Islanding Operation

When the grid is connected:

The grid-connected controller operates.

When the grid is disconnected:

The islanding controller automatically takes over.

Switching between these modes is controlled by a logical switch “g”.

6. Islanding Mode (g = 0)

Run the system in islanding mode.

Initially:

Solar power is constant.

Wind power is slightly varying.

The AC load varies due to an asynchronous machine (ASM):

Starting conditions cause variations in load.

The battery charges due to solar and wind power.

7. Effect of Changing Solar Power

When solar value is set to a higher value (e.g., 500):

PV power decreases.

Battery power increases.

8. Load Behavior

When load is applied:

No change in load voltage and load current is observed.

No change in PCC voltage and current.

This stability is maintained by the battery.

If the battery is absent:

Load voltage would decrease.

9. Effect of Wind Power Changes

If wind power decreases:

Battery power increases.

Load remains unaffected.

10. When Wind and Solar are Zero

If both wind and solar power are set to zero:

The battery alone supplies the load.
